                        <additions>
                            <p>
                                <locus from="LCI" to="LCI" scheme="other"/>
                                <note>Top of page, in brown ink by an early modern hand: <quote>Soror Maria Elisabetha <add place="above">Monica</add> Hansen prediger ordens ora pro Me an gottes segen ist alles gelegen laus Deo semper 1695</quote>; bottom left corner: National Library book label.</note>
                            </p>
                            <p>
                                <locus from="SL1r" to="SL1r" scheme="folios"/>
                                <note>Top of page, brown ink by an early modern hand: <quote>Soror Maria Anna Rosae Gessers</quote>.</note>
                            </p>
                            <p>
                                <locus from="SL1v" to="SL1v" scheme="folios"/>
                                <note>Top of page, in brown ink by an early modern hand: <quote>Bernhard Rosenblad</quote>, <quote>18-25</quote>.</note>
                            </p>
                        </additions>
                        <bindingDesc>
                            <binding contemporary="unknown">
                                <p>Medieval or early modern binding. Brown leather over wooden boards. 3 double raised bands and endbands. Originally, two brass clasps. <locus from="Spine" to="Spine" scheme="other"/>, stamped in gold: <quote>A 184</quote>.</p>
                                <p>
                                    <dimensions type="binding">
                                        <height quantity="120" unit="mm"/>
                                        <width quantity="90" unit="mm"/>
                                        <depth quantity="60" unit="mm"/>
                                    </dimensions>
                                </p>
                                <decoNote type="tooling">
                                    <p>Simple tooling consisting of a double frame and some and triangular shapes ending in silver floral shape by the bands.</p>
                                </decoNote>
                                <condition>Leather worn. One clasp missing.</condition>
                            </binding>
                        </bindingDesc>
                    </physDesc>
                    <history>
                        <origin>
                            <p>
                                <origPlace>
                                    <placeName ref="https://www.manuscripta.se/place/100104">Germany</placeName>
                                </origPlace>,<origDate notAfter="1475" notBefore="1426"> 15th century, middle</origDate>. The manuscript was likely made for a Dominican monastery, perhaps <placeName ref="https://www.manuscripta.se/place/100377">St Gertrud's</placeName> in <placeName ref="https://www.manuscripta.se/place/100014">Cologne</placeName>. The manuscript contains an office for both St Dominic and St Gertrud, and mentions a chuch of St Gertrud on <locus from="178r" to="178r" scheme="folios"/>. Both saints are also given prominence in the two litanies (<locus from="102v" to="102v" scheme="folios"/>, <locus from="103r" to="103r" scheme="folios"/>, <locus from="148v" to="148v" scheme="folios"/>). The long list of female saints in the litanies (<locus from="103r" to="103v" scheme="folios"/>, <locus from="148v" to="148v" scheme="folios"/>) and the instructions for sister, on e.g. <locus from="173r" to="173r" scheme="folios"/>, gives further support for a nunnary as place of origin.</p>
                        </origin>
                        <provenance>
                            <p>On <locus from="SL1r" to="SL1r" scheme="folios"/> there are two notes by previous owners from the 17th century: Soror <persName ref="https://www.manuscripta.se/person/102778">Maria Elisabetha Monica Hansen</persName> and Soror <persName ref="https://www.manuscripta.se/person/102779">Maria Anna Rosa Gesser</persName>, sisters in a Dominican convent (<quote>prediger ordens</quote>). It is possible that the manuscript remained at St Gertrud's until the secularisation around year 1800. Later In the 19th century, the manuscript belonged to <persName ref="https://www.manuscripta.se/person/101021">Bernhard Rosenblad</persName> (see note on <locus from="SL1v" to="SL1v" scheme="folios"/>). It was purchased from him by <persName ref="https://www.manuscripta.se/person/102612">G. J. R. Gordon</persName>.</p>
                        </provenance>
                        <acquisition>
                            <p>Purchased from <persName ref="https://www.manuscripta.se/person/102612">G. J. R. Gordon</persName> by the <orgName ref="https://www.manuscripta.se/org/100004">National Library of Sweden</orgName> in <date when="1845"/>.</p>
                        </acquisition>
                    </history>
